Malaysia’s Ringgit Weakens as Euro Debt Concerns Reduce Demand

-- B y   E l f f i e   C h e w
-- 
2011-07-18T08:51:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-18/malaysia-s-ringgit-weakens-as-euro-debt-concerns-reduce-demand.html
Malaysia’s ringgit weakened for a
second day as lingering concerns over  Europe ’s debt crisis
damped demand for emerging-market assets.  The ringgit fell along with other Asian currencies as
European leaders seek to revamp their debt crisis-fighting
strategy and break a deadlock later this week. Malaysia may
report on July 20 inflation quickened to 3.6 percent in June
from 3.3 percent in May, the most since March 2009, according to
a Bloomberg News survey.  “Risk-appetite is on the low side as debt issues in Europe
are still plaguing Asian currencies,” said Suresh Kumar
Ramanathan, a currency strategist at CIMB Investment Bank Bhd.
in Kuala Lumpur. “Malaysia’s inflation data may not have much
impact.”  The ringgit dropped 0.3 percent to 3.0140 per dollar as of
4:43 p.m. in Kuala Lumpur, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg.  A leaders’ summit on July 21 will discuss the financial
stability of the region and  Greece ’s debt program, European
Union President Herman van Rompuy said in a July 15 statement.
Among topics for the talks is a potential overhaul of the 440-
billion euro ($623 billion) rescue fund to enable Greece to
better pay its bills.  Bank Negara  kept its overnight policy rate unchanged at 3
percent on July 7, citing higher downside risks to growth amid
Europe’s debt crisis and slowing U.S. growth, which have damped
the outlook for exports.  Government bonds  were little changed. The yield on the 4.16
percent debt due July 2021 held at 3.86 percent, according to
Bursa Malaysia Bhd.  To contact the reporter on this story:
